An aside, I'd suggest batch priming rather than bottle priming.  Check out
http://www.howtobrew.com/section1/chapter11-4.html
for details.  That probably won't give longer lasting bubbles, however.

Long lasting bubbles are a result of proteins in the beer.

If I remember from earlier posts, you use kits, right?  To add protein,
you may have to do some type of mini-mash.  Just mini-mashing some barley
malt may be enough.  However, many folks use oats or wheat in their
mash to help head retention.  (You can get flaked wheat from your Local
Homebrew Shop (LHBS)).

A mini-mash is pretty simple... just put some barley malt in some
hot water to around 150F and keep it around 150F for 30 minutes or so
(stick it into an oven, set to the lowest warming setting, for example.
The consistancy should be a little wetter than porridge.  After 30 or
more minutes, strain it out with a strainer into your boiling pot and
flush it with a little hot water (do not squeeze it).  Continue to boil
and the rest is your usual procedure.

For an example of grains, you might use a lb of &quot;pale malt&quot; or perhaps
1/2 lb of &quot;pale malt&quot; and 1/4 lb of &quot;instant&quot; oats used for oatmeal.
(You always have to have 1/2 or more of some sort of &quot;malt&quot; - pure grains
like oatmeal, corn flakes, flaked wheat, flaked barley, etc. have no
active enzymes and will not convert the starch to sugar during the mash).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The beer is clear (although it clouds if chilled),
">

That's just chill haze.  It doesn't matter, except for looks.  If you
refrigerate the bottles for 3 or 4 weeks, the haze will usually all
settle out and stay out as long as it is kept cold.

Derric
