You can, but then you stir up a lot of the sediment when trying to mix in the
sugar.  The standard way of doing it is to put your priming sugar into a
seperate &quot;bottling bucket&quot; and transfer the beer out of the fermenter into
that.  Then you fill the bottles from the bottling bucket.  That way you
know that you're getting an even distribution of the sugar in each bottle.
Trying to measure out and fill each bottle with sugar is a real pain, and it's
very easy to make a mistake (a bit too much sugar in one bottle, a bit too
little in another, woops I forgot to prime that bottle, uh oh I added sugar
twice to another one.... etc).  IMO, measuring and dumping sugar once into
the bottling bucket is a lot easier.

John.
