That *COULD* happen over a very long period and would be called &quot;yeast
autolysis.&quot;

However, for weeks or a month, there's no problem with it on the &quot;sludge.&quot;
((You'll more often see that &quot;sludge&quot; referred to as &quot;spent yeast,&quot;
&quot;trub,&quot; or (in winemaking) &quot;lees.&quot;))

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I've had a 'lager' sitting on the sludge since it stopped fermenting weeks
&gt; ago.... I almost got round to bottling it this weekend just gone. Stashing
&gt; it in a nice clean bucket might bu me some more time!
">

Yes it would.  Generally, most folks' procedure on this newsgroup is:
1. Ferment in a &quot;primary&quot; fermenter for a week or two
2. Siphon into a &quot;secondary&quot; fermenter for another week or two.
3. (For a lager, it might then be dropped to 33F and held for
many weeks for &quot;lagering.&quot;)
4. Siphon into a &quot;bottling bucket&quot; (on top of boiled sugar/water
priming solution) for bottling.
Ideally, the primary fermenter might be any bucket, the secondary might
be glass (for oxygen free longer storage periods), and the bottling
bucket might have a spigot.  In the real world, you use what you have
available! :)

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; But can you just tip it back into the cleaned fermenter for bottling? It's
&gt; much easier, as there's a tap on it (for bottling).
">

Yes, that would be ok.  Some on here would say not to do that becuase
every time you move your beer around, you possibly expose it to more
oxygen, which will cause your beer to stale more quickly.  However,
since you mention in another post that you drink up your beer quickly,
the oxidation probably isn't an issue (it would take months to notice).
Just be careful transferring it and don't splash or foam it up!

OR... maybe you can switch your primary and secondary containers so that
the spigot bucket is free at bottling time --- or install a spigot in
all of them (just be aware that they may start to drip/leak over time
and keep spares handy).

