No problem.  I didn't really care (and wasn't trying to rag on you), but I've
seen people get confused by the terms before so thought I'd try and clarify
incase ant didn't understand.

If you don't care, just hit delete now.  ;)

Basically, a secondary fermenter refers to another vessel used during the
fermentation of the beer.  There's only one fermentation, but it occurs in
two containers, the &quot;primary fermenter&quot; and &quot;secondary fermenter&quot;.

A secondary fermentation refers to starting a new fermentation after the
original one has completed.  Most of the time you see this term used in the
commercial world they're talking about &quot;naturally carbonated&quot; beer.  IOW,
adding priming sugar to the bottles creates a secondary fermentation, which
is where the carbonation comes from.  We don't really give this a special
name in homebrewing.

One refers to the number of containers, the other refers to the number of
fermentations.

